paragraphs.text:
%md

## Data Science in Apache Spark 
#### Exploring the Global Terrorism Database Dataset

**Level**: Moderate
**Language**: Scala
**Requirements**: 
- [HDP 2.5](http://hortonworks.com/products/sandbox/) (or later) or [HDCloud](https://hortonworks.github.io/hdp-aws/)
- Spark 2.x
- Download [GTDB dataset] (https://www.kaggle.com/START-UMD/gtd)

**Author**: Ian Brooks
**Follow** [LinkedIn - Ian Brooks PhD] (https://www.linkedin.com/in/ianrbrooksphd/)


####Context
Information on more than 150,000 Terrorist Attacks

The Global Terrorism Database (GTD) is an open-source database including information on terrorist attacks around the world from 1970 through 2015 (with annual updates planned for the future). The GTD includes systematic data on domestic as well as international terrorist incidents that have occurred during this time period and now includes more than 150,000 cases. The database is maintained by researchers at the National Consortium for the Study of Terrorism and Responses to Terrorism (START), headquartered at the University of Maryland. [More Information] (http://start.umd.edu/gtd/)

paragraphs.text:
%md
###SparkContext Variable

In the following paragraph, we will define and initalize the SparkContext variable that will be used in future steps of the lab.  The SparkContext variable is the main entry point for Spark functionality. A SparkContext represents the connection to a Spark cluster, and can be used to create RDDs, accumulators and broadcast variables on that cluster.

[More Information](https://spark.apache.org/docs/2.0.0/api/java/org/apache/spark/SparkContext.html)

%md

###Data Loading and Schema Inference

In the following paragraph, we will load the dataset, which is a CSV file, and infer the schema using Spark's toolset.  After the import, we will print the schema of the resuling dataframe.  Before this step can be completed, we must first load the CSV file into HDFS.  Please review the following [tutorial on data loading] (http://hortonworks.com/hadoop-tutorial/loading-data-into-the-hortonworks-sandbox/) for reference.

paragraphs.title: Import Dataset into Dataframe and Print Schema
paragraphs.text:
%spark
import org.apache.spark.sql.types._
import org.apache.spark.sql.DataFrame
import scala.collection.mutable.ListBuffer

//Create a data frame from CSV File 
val df_WholeSetRaw = sqlContext.read.format("com.databricks.spark.csv").option("header", "true").option("inferSchema", "true").load("hdfs://sandbox.hortonworks.com:8020/tmp/globalterrorismdb_0616dist.csv")

//Correcting the column names of Latitude and Longitude 
val df_WholeSetRaw1 = df_WholeSetRaw.withColumnRenamed("latitude", "Longitude_Coord")
val df_WholeSetRaw2 = df_WholeSetRaw1.withColumnRenamed("longitude","Latitude_Coord")

val df_WholeSet = df_WholeSetRaw2
df_WholeSet.cache()

//Create Table from DataFrame
//df_WholeSet.registerTempTable("EventTable")

df_WholeSet.sqlContext.sparkContext
df_WholeSet.sqlContext

   
//Display resulting Infered schema 
df_WholeSet.printSchema()

paragraphs.text:
%md
###Data Cleaning
In the following paragraph, we will clean the dataset by remove the Null values and replace them with 0.  This is an important steps to make the data more machine friendly for future analysis. Fortunately for us, Spark Dataframes provides many diffent methods for handling Null values in the dataset.  Please review the following [Spark API document] (http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/api/scala/index.html#org.apache.spark.sql.DataFrameNaFunctions) for reference.  After we run the following paragraph, notice how the Null values have been replaced in the dataframe.

paragraphs.title: Covariance and Correlation
Setting Up Map Points
paragraphs.text:
%spark 

val df_MapSetDirty = df_WholeSet.select("iyear","nkill","Latitude_Coord","Longitude_Coord","weaptype1_txt","country_txt","city")

val df_MapSet = df_MapSetDirty.na.fill(0)

val df_USAEvents = df_MapSet.filter("nkill >= 25 ")

df_MapSet.registerTempTable("MapSet")

z.angularBind("MapEvents", df_USAEvents.take(1000))

paragraphs.text:
%md 
#K-Means Clustering Example 
###Feature Transformation - Categorical Data

In this particular dataset, there are features, such as attack type, weapon type, target type, and region type, that are known as categotical data.  These features can be used in tradional SQL like queies, but they can not be used in their current state in machine learning algorithms.  I have written an [HCC article] (https://community.hortonworks.com/articles/75295/spark-categorical-data-transformation.html) that goes into greater detail on this subject.  To complete this task, we will use the OneHotEncoder to convert the categorical values into a vector that can be later used to feed our ML algorithms.  Please review the following [Spark API document] (http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/api/scala/index.html#org.apache.spark.ml.feature.OneHotEncoder) for reference.

In the following paragraph, we will select the features that we will ultimately feed into the ML algorithm.

###Reviewing Results of K-Means
In the following paragraph, we will print and review the results on the K-Means model.  We will first display the K-Means Cost value, which is the average distance of all events from their assigned clusters.  The goal is minimize this value, which can be accomplished by increasing the numbers of clusters.  After the K-Means cost value has been printed, the final center information is printed for cluster.
